    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1]]></fr:tex> be a sub-object of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, in the category of continuous families of Hodge <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structures.
      We will show that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1]]></fr:tex> is a direct factor of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> in this category.
      We can suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> to be homogeneous.
      If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\psi ]]></fr:tex> is a polarisation form for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, then the orthogonal of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1]]></fr:tex> with respect to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\psi ]]></fr:tex> is indeed a sub-object of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> that is a supplement to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1]]></fr:tex>.
      This proves (i)</fr:p>

    <fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is of weight <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, then a polarisation of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> defines an isomorphism between <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\otimes \mathbb {Q}(n)]]></fr:tex>.
      By <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.1"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.1.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="4.2.2.1" />, we thus have that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>.
      For arbitrary <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, if we decompose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> into its homogeneous components, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*=\bigoplus _n(H^n)^*]]></fr:tex>, whence again <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>.
      Finally, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\wedge ^p H]]></fr:tex> is a direct factor of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigotimes ^p H]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Hom}(H_1,H_2)\simeq  H_1^*\otimes  H_2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
